  <h2>Accurate Answers When Your Pet Needs Them</h2>
  <p>
    When your pet is sick, accurate and timely diagnostics are essential for effective treatment. At Healthy Paws Animal Hospital, our in-house laboratory allows us to run critical tests and get results in minutes — not days. This means faster diagnosis, faster treatment decisions, and less time spent wondering what's going on with your pet.
  </p>
  <p>
    We also use routine diagnostics as a cornerstone of preventive care. Regular bloodwork and screening tests help us establish a healthy baseline for your pet and detect subtle changes long before symptoms appear.
  </p>

  <h2>Our In-House Diagnostic Capabilities</h2>

  <h3>Complete Blood Count (CBC)</h3>
  <p>
    A CBC evaluates your pet's red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. This test helps us identify infections, anemia, blood clotting disorders, immune system conditions, and certain cancers. It's one of the most commonly run tests in veterinary medicine and provides a broad overview of your pet's health.
  </p>

  <h3>Comprehensive Blood Chemistry Panel</h3>
  <p>
    Blood chemistry panels measure organ function and metabolic status. We evaluate kidney values, liver enzymes, blood glucose, electrolytes, protein levels, and more. These results help us assess how well your pet's major organs are functioning and can identify conditions like kidney disease, diabetes, liver disease, and hormonal imbalances.
  </p>

  <h3>Urinalysis</h3>
  <p>
    Urinalysis provides valuable information about kidney function, hydration status, urinary tract infections, bladder crystals, diabetes, and other conditions. We analyze the physical properties of the urine, its chemical composition, and examine the sediment under a microscope for cells, bacteria, and crystals.
  </p>

  <h3>Fecal Analysis</h3>
  <p>
    Intestinal parasites are common in pets and often don't cause visible symptoms in the early stages. Fecal testing allows us to detect parasites like roundworms, hookworms, whipworms, coccidia, and giardia. We recommend annual fecal testing as part of your pet's <a href="/wellness-exams-lake-in-the-hills-il/">wellness exam</a>, even if they appear healthy.
  </p>

  <h3>Cytology</h3>
  <p>
    When your pet develops a lump, skin lesion, or unusual discharge, cytology helps us determine what's happening at the cellular level. A small sample is collected — usually with a fine needle aspirate, which is quick and minimally uncomfortable — and examined under our microscope. In-house cytology gives us rapid initial results that guide whether further testing, monitoring, or treatment is needed.
  </p>

  <h3>Additional Testing</h3>
  <p>
    Our in-house capabilities also include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Thyroid testing</strong> — screening for hypothyroidism in dogs and hyperthyroidism in cats</li>
    <li><strong>Heartworm testing</strong> — annual screening for this serious parasitic disease</li>
    <li><strong>Tick-borne disease screening</strong> — testing for Lyme disease, ehrlichiosis, and anaplasmosis</li>
    <li><strong>Pancreatic testing</strong> — evaluation for pancreatitis</li>
    <li><strong>Blood clotting tests</strong> — pre-surgical coagulation screening</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For specialized tests such as hormone panels, allergy testing, or histopathology, we work with trusted outside reference laboratories and typically have results within one to three business days.
  </p>

  <h2>Why In-House Diagnostics Matter</h2>
  <p>
    Having a laboratory on-site makes a meaningful difference in your pet's care:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Same-day results</strong> — Most common tests are completed in 15 to 30 minutes, so we can discuss findings and begin treatment during the same visit</li>
    <li><strong>Faster emergency response</strong> — When your pet arrives for <a href="/emergency-urgent-care/">urgent care</a>, rapid diagnostics help us make critical treatment decisions without delay</li>
    <li><strong>Fewer follow-up visits</strong> — Getting answers on the spot means less back-and-forth for you and less stress for your pet</li>
    <li><strong>Better surgical safety</strong> — <a href="/surgery/">Pre-surgical bloodwork</a> is run and reviewed the same day, confirming your pet is safe for anesthesia before proceeding</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Diagnostics as Preventive Care</h2>
  <p>
    We recommend annual bloodwork for all adult pets and semi-annual screening for <a href="/senior-pet-care-lake-in-the-hills-il/">senior pets</a> (typically seven years and older). Regular testing allows us to establish your pet's individual baseline values and detect subtle trends — like a kidney value slowly rising over time — that might not be obvious from a single test. Catching these changes early gives us the best opportunity to intervene before a condition becomes serious.
  </p>
